## The Comparison Everyone Gets Wrong

With the 2026 FIFA World Cup driving millions in volume across prediction markets, a question keeps surfacing in trading communities: isn't Polymarket just sports betting with extra steps? The short answer is no. The longer answer explains why that distinction matters for your wallet. Polymarket vs sports betting represents a fundamental difference in market structure, not just a branding exercise. Understanding these differences separates traders who consistently profit from those who treat prediction markets like another DraftKings tab.

## How Odds Actually Form

Traditional sportsbooks employ teams of oddsmakers who set lines based on proprietary models, then adjust based on action. The house maintains a built-in edge through vigorish, typically around 4-5% on standard bets. When you bet on Norway to win the World Cup at a sportsbook, you're betting against the house's assessment. Polymarket operates on a completely different model. Prices emerge from peer-to-peer trading where buyers and sellers continuously negotiate fair value. There is no house setting odds. When the Norway World Cup market shows approximately 2.5 cents, that price reflects the aggregate assessment of thousands of independent traders putting real capital behind their views. This mechanism tends to produce more accurate probability estimates over time because prices incorporate information from anyone willing to stake money on their beliefs.

## The Liquidity Question

Sportsbooks guarantee liquidity. Place a bet, it's accepted instantly at the posted odds. Prediction markets require someone on the other side of your trade. This creates both challenges and opportunities. On [Polymarket](https://polymarket.com/?r=POLYTips), major markets like the Iran peace deal or World Cup outcomes maintain deep order books with millions in liquidity. You can enter and exit positions of significant size without moving the price. Smaller markets behave differently. Thin liquidity means wider spreads and potential slippage. Sophisticated traders learn to read order books and time entries accordingly. The liquidity structure also enables something sportsbooks cannot offer: the ability to exit positions before resolution. If you buy Yes on a market at 20 cents and breaking news pushes it to 60 cents, you can sell immediately and lock in profit without waiting for the event to conclude.

